astro-ph/0601172 [abs, ps, pdf, other] :
          Title:  The role of kink instability in Poynting-flux dominated
          jets
          Authors:   Dimitrios  Giannios,  Henk  C.  Spruit  (Max  Planck
          Institute for Astrophysics)
          Comments: 13 pages, 7 figures, accepted for publication in A&A
          The  role  of  kink  instability in magnetically driven jets is
          explored  through numerical one-dimensional steady relativistic
          MHD  calculations. The instability is shown to have enough time
          to  grow  and influence the dynamics of Poynting-flux dominated
          jets.  In  the  case of AGN jets, the flow becomes kinetic flux
          dominated  at  distances  larger  than ~1000 r_g because of the
          rapid  dissipation  of  Poynting  flux.  When  applied  to  GRB
          outflows,  the model predicts more gradual Poynting dissipation
          and  moderately  magnetized  flow  at  distances of ~10^{16} cm
          where  the  deceleration  of  the ejecta due to its interaction
          with  the  external  medium is expected. The energy released by
          the  instability can power the compact ``blazar zone'' emission
          and  the  prompt  emission  of GRB outflows with high radiative
          efficiencies.


   
