          We  present  radio observations of the unique, recently formed,
          planetary  nebula (PN) associated with a very long-period OH/IR
          variable  star  V1018  Sco  that  is unequivocally still in its
          asymptoticgiant  branch  phase.  Two regions within the optical
          nebula  are  clearly  detected  in  nonthermal  radio continuum
          emission,  with radio spectral indices comparable to those seen
          in  colliding-wind  Wolf-Rayet  binaries. We suggest that these
          represent  shocked  interactions  between the hot, fast stellar
          wind  and  the cold nebular shell that represents the PN's slow
          wind  moving  away  from  the central star. This same interface
          produces  both  synchrotron  radio continuum and the optical PN
          emission.  The  fast  wind is neither spherical in geometry nor
          aligned  withany  obvious optical or radio axis. We also report
