          Authors:  Steven  H.  Pravdo,  Stuart  B.  Shaklan,  Sloane  J.
          Wiktorowicz,  Shri Kulkarni, James P. Lloyd, Frantz Martinache,
          Peter G. Tuthill, Michael J. Ireland
          Comments: 25 pages, 8 figures, accepted for ApJ
          The  Stellar  Planet  Survey  (STEPS) is an ongoing astrometric
          search  for  giant  planets and brown dwarfs around a sample of
          ~30 M-dwarfs. We have discovered several low-mass companions by
          measuring  the  motion  of  our  target stars relative to their
          reference  frames.  The  highest  mass  discovery thus far is G
          78-28B, a companion to the M-dwarf G 78-28A. The orbital period
          is  4.18 +/- 0.03 y, the system mass is 0.565 +/- 0.055 Msolar,
          and   the   semi-major  axis  is  2.19  +/-  0.10  AU.  Imaging
          observations  with  the  Keck  laser guide star adaptive optics
          (LGSAO)  and the Palomar AO instruments resolved the system and
          also  yielded  JHK-band  delta  magnitudes.  We use the orbital
          solution,  light  ratios,  and mass-luminosity relationships to
          derive component masses of MA = 0.370 +/- 0.034 Msolar and MB =
          0.195 +/- 0.021 Msolar. G 78-28B is of type M4 V based upon its
          colors  and  mass. We also discovered GJ 231.1C, a companion to
          GJ  231.1B,  with STEPS and imaged the companion with LGSAO and
          Palomar AO, but the orbital period is longer than our observing
